          "id": "spin-a-top",
          "title": "Spin a Top",
          "shortDescription": "Spin a hand-spun top so that it remains upright.",
          "description": "Spin a top so that it remains upright.",
          "justification": "Spin a Top evaluates a system's ability to exploit object dynamics to achieve a desired outcome. The task involves dynamic direct manipulation of a rigid object whose dimensions are small relative to the hand and requires generating an appropriate combination of orientation, angular velocity, and release conditions for successful execution. Unlike many dexterous manipulation tasks that are primarily quasistatic, spinning a top depends critically on dynamic interactions and the transfer of momentum from the hand to the object. The task exhibits moderate constraint complexity, as successful performance requires coordinating grasping, rotational motion, and release timing while maintaining control of the object up to the point of disengagement. It also involves significant constraint change, progressing from stable grasping to dynamic release, after which the object's behavior is governed entirely by its interaction with the environment. Because the top's stability depends on the quality of the imparted spin, small errors in orientation, velocity, or release timing can lead to immediate failure. More broadly, spinning a top serves as a representative benchmark for dynamic dexterous manipulation, evaluating a manipulator's ability to intentionally exploit physical dynamics rather than relying solely on precise quasistatic control.",
